Viewing seasonal distribution

week_limit <-
  function(x) {
    c(floor_date(min(x), "week"), 
      ceiling_date(max(x) - weeks(1), "year"))
  }

proviso_sales %>%
  mutate(sale_date = as_datetime(sale_date),
         sale_date = as_date(sale_date), # I feel like this is suboptimal
         sale_week = floor_date(sale_date, "week"),
         sale_week = as.Date(sale_week)
         ) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = sale_week)) +
  geom_histogram(fill = "skyblue", color = "black") +  
  facet_wrap(~ year, ncol = 1, scales = "free_x") +
  scale_x_date(date_labels = "%b %d",
               limits = week_limit) + # close enough for now
  labs(
    title = "Histogram of Sales by Week",
    x = "Week",
    y = "Frequency"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

I thought this would be better but I dont think it is.

proviso_sales %>%

Viewing exceptions noted in the documentation

The dataset documentation notes that each row is a sale, and some properties may be sold multiple times in one year. It also notes that previous versions filtered out sales less than 10k and by deed type. Through summarizing, we see that there are not many instances where these filters are relevant.

# view exceptions noted in documentation counts
proviso_sales %>%
  summarize(n(),
            sum(sale_filter_same_sale_within_365),
            sum(sale_filter_less_than_10k),
            sum(sale_filter_deed_type)) %>% 
  DT::datatable()

Investigate Missing Variables

assessments variables are mostly complete, with the exception of board_ variables that are 0.666 complete. Grouping by year, we can see that these are mainly missing in 2023 and less in 2022, but no missing values in 2021. This suggests that the board of review assessments are not yet complete. The documentation supports this conclusion.

# investigate missing variables
proviso_assess %>% 
  group_by(tax_year) %>% 
  summarize(bldg_na = sum(is.na(board_bldg)),
            land_na = sum(is.na(board_bldg)),
            tot_na = sum(is.na(board_tot))) %>% 
  DT::datatable()

Skim Results

characteristics is mostly missing tieback_key_pin, other variables with missing values are more than 0.885 complete. However, it only has data for 2023.

The documentation notes that the Assessor recently changed how Home Improvement Exceptions (HIE) work, in order to encourage property improvements. Records prior to 2021 do not include HIE characteristics.

Each row is an improvement, but some improvements count as a renovation or that variable is capturing improvements from prior years. Some properties have multiple improvements.

Analysis

Simple Sales

Simple sales still includes properties that are sold multiple times a year. As we look to the next section, we consider what is the price of the property that the assessor is aiming for? Within a year, the sale price can vary dramatically for one property.

# this creates a warning for pins without any non-missing values in num_parcels_sale
simple_sales <- proviso_sales %>%
  group_by(pin) %>% 
  mutate(multisale = max(is_multisale, na.rm = T), # using max jic
         parcels = max(num_parcels_sale, na.rm = T)) %>%
  ungroup() %>% 
  filter(multisale == 0,
         parcels == 1) %>% 
  # select out single value variables
  select(!c(sale_type, is_mydec_date, is_multisale, num_parcels_sale, multisale,
            parcels))

Plot Trends

The assessors office faced criticism for regressive assessment ratio. In this part of the assignment, we can do a simple check by looking at the difference in assessment to average sales price. In our graph, we see that there is still tendency to overestimate lower value properties and underestimate higher value properties. The latter issue maybe gets better by 2023, but it is hard to tell.

# Want the figure to be square, so width is 3x the height

est_tbl <- join_tbl %>% 
  group_by(pin, year) %>% 
  summarize(avg_sale = mean(sale_price),
            certified = mean(certified_tot)) %>% 
  # These are residential properties in cook county so, assessed value is 10% of estimate
  mutate(estimate = certified / 0.1)

# dplyr gets mad about $ syntax now, but pull isn't exactly eloquent
min_l <- min(pull(est_tbl, estimate), pull(est_tbl, avg_sale), na.rm=T)

# Figuring out scale range took too long
scale_range = c(min_l, NA)
scale_range = c(10000, NA)

more_labs = scales::trans_breaks("log10", function(x) 10^x)

scale_args <- list(labels = scales::dollar,
                   limits = scale_range,
                   breaks = more_labs,
                   minor_breaks = NULL)

saveRDS(scale_args, "part1_scale_args.rds")

sale_v_est <-
  est_tbl %>% 
    ggplot(aes(x = estimate, 
               y = avg_sale)) + 
    geom_point(color = "lightblue") +
    geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0,
                linetype = "dashed", linewidth = 1.5) +
    do.call(scale_x_log10, scale_args) +
    do.call(scale_y_log10, scale_args) +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(legend.position = "bottom",
          panel.spacing = unit(0.05, "lines"),
          panel.border = element_rect(color = "black", fill = NA, linewidth = 1), 
          strip.background = element_rect(color = "black", linewidth = 1)) +
    facet_wrap(~year, nrow = 1) +
    guides(x = guide_axis(angle = 30))

Part 2

Part A - Introduction

Background

To facilitate the fair execution of the property tax system, the Cook County Assessors office assesses the market value of every property in Cook County through over a triennial cycle. From known characteristics of properties sold, the assessors office models the market value of all properties whether or not they were recently sold. However, there are limitations with any estimation attempt due to incomplete knowledge and the natural tendency of models to estimate towards the average.

Visualizations

3 to 4 graphs with descriptive captions which include information on sale price, assessment accuracy, and outliers. Generally focus on single family homes and arms length transactions. Are there data you would exclude?

Im not sure how to identify non-arms length transactions.

Of the 200 level regression classes, only 210, 211, 212 and 295 could be a multi-family home (MFH). However, none are included in the Proviso records.

assess23_split <- initial_split(model_assess_23)

assess23_train <- training(assess23_split)
assess23_test  <- testing(assess23_split)
 
# # reduce folds to decrease time to fit
folds_assess23 <- vfold_cv(assess23_train, v=5)

rf_reg_recipe <- 
  recipe(log_sale_price ~ # maybe include nbhd_code?
           class + cdu + pin_is_multiland + pin_num_landlines + char_yrblt + 
           char_bldg_sf + char_land_sf + char_beds + char_rooms + char_fbath + 
           char_hbath + char_frpl + char_type_resd + char_cnst_qlty + 
           char_apts + char_attic_fnsh + char_gar1_att + char_gar1_area + 
           char_gar1_size + char_gar1_cnst + char_attic_type + char_bsmt + 
           char_ext_wall + char_heat + char_repair_cnd + char_bsmt_fin + 
           char_roof_cnst + char_use + char_site + char_renovation + 
           recent_renovation + char_porch + char_air + char_tp_plan, 
         data = assess23_train) %>% 
  step_novel(all_nominal_predictors()) %>% 
  step_unknown(all_nominal_predictors()) %>%
  # this step requires string, factor, or ordered columns
  # step_unknown(all_predictors()) %>%
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors(), one_hot = T)

rf_reg_recipe %>% 
  prep() %>% 
  bake(assess23_train) %>% 
  sample_n(10) %>% 
  DT::datatable()
rf_reg_mod <- 
  rand_forest() %>%
  set_mode("regression") %>% 
  set_engine("ranger", importance = "impurity") 
  
rf_reg_wf <-
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(rf_reg_mod) %>% 
  add_recipe(rf_reg_recipe)

# maybe knit above and read in model tb as rds for performance
part3_sold_23 <-
  part3_tb %>% 
  filter(!is.na(sale_price)) %>% 
  drop_na()

part3_sold_23_split <- initial_split(part3_sold_23)

part3_sold_23_train <- training(part3_sold_23_split)
part3_sold_23_test  <- testing(part3_sold_23_split)
 
# # reduce folds to decrease time to fit
folds_assess23 <- vfold_cv(part3_sold_23_train, v=5)

p3_sold_23_recipe <- 
  recipe(log_sale_price ~ # maybe include nbhd_code?
           class + cdu + pin_is_multiland + pin_num_landlines + char_yrblt + 
           char_bldg_sf + char_land_sf + char_beds + char_rooms + char_fbath + 
           char_hbath + char_frpl + char_type_resd + char_cnst_qlty + 
           char_apts + char_attic_fnsh + char_gar1_att + char_gar1_area + 
           char_gar1_size + char_gar1_cnst + char_attic_type + char_bsmt + 
           char_ext_wall + char_heat + char_repair_cnd + char_bsmt_fin + 
           char_roof_cnst + char_use + char_site + char_renovation + 
           recent_renovation + char_porch + char_air + char_tp_plan +
           nearest_golf_course_dist_ft, 
         data = part3_sold_23_train) %>% 
  #step_impute_knn(all_predictors()) %>% 
  # Handle new levels in categorical variables
  step_other(all_nominal(), threshold = 0.05) %>%
    step_novel(all_nominal_predictors()) %>% 
  step_unknown(all_nominal_predictors()) %>%
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors(), one_hot = F)

normalized_rec <-
  p3_sold_23_recipe %>%
  #step_zy(all_predictors()) %>% I swear this function exists on my other pc 
  step_zv(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_predictors())

poly_recipe <-
  p3_sold_23_recipe %>%
  step_interact(~ all_predictors():all_predictors())

baked <-
  p3_sold_23_recipe %>% 
    prep() %>% 
    bake(part3_sold_23_train) %>% 
    sample_n(10) 

baked %>% 
  DT::datatable()
p3_sold_23_model <- 
  rand_forest() %>%
  set_mode("regression") %>% 
  set_engine("ranger", importance = "impurity") 
  
p3_sold_23_wf <-
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(p3_sold_23_model) %>% 
  add_recipe(p3_sold_23_recipe)
# Final models
linear_reg_spec <- 
   linear_reg(penalty = tune(), mixture = tune()) %>% 
   set_engine("glmnet")

# 56 seconds
nnet_spec <- 
   mlp(hidden_units = tune(), penalty = tune(), epochs = tune()) %>% 
   set_engine("nnet", MaxNWts = 2600) %>% 
   set_mode("regression")

# 13 seconds
mars_spec <- 
   mars(prod_degree = tune()) %>%  #<- use GCV to choose terms
   set_engine("earth") %>% 
   set_mode("regression")

# radial: 22 seconds
svm_r_spec <- 
   svm_rbf(cost = tune(), rbf_sigma = tune()) %>% 
   set_engine("kernlab") %>% 
   set_mode("regression")

# poly: 12 minutes 38 seconds
svm_p_spec <- 
   svm_poly(cost = tune(), degree = tune()) %>% 
   set_engine("kernlab") %>% 
   set_mode("regression")

# 2 minutes 8 seconds
knn_spec <- 
   nearest_neighbor(neighbors = tune(), dist_power = tune()) %>% #, weight_func = tune()) %>% 
   set_engine("kknn") %>% 
   set_mode("regression")

# 15 seconds
cart_spec <- 
   decision_tree(cost_complexity = tune(), min_n = tune()) %>% 
   set_engine("rpart") %>% 
   set_mode("regression")

# 30 seconds
bag_cart_spec <- 
   bag_tree() %>% 
   set_engine("rpart", times = 50L) %>% 
   set_mode("regression")

# 45 seconds
rf_spec <- 
   rand_forest(mtry = tune(), min_n = tune(), trees = 250) %>% 
   set_engine("ranger") %>% 
   set_mode("regression")

# boosting: 2 minutes 51 seconds
xgb_spec <- 
   boost_tree(tree_depth = tune(), learn_rate = tune(), loss_reduction = tune(), 
              min_n = tune(), sample_size = tune(), trees = tune()) %>% 
   set_engine("xgboost") %>% 
   set_mode("regression")

# 1 min 23 seconds
cubist_spec <- 
   cubist_rules(committees = tune(), neighbors = tune()) %>% 
   set_engine("Cubist") 

nnet_param <- 
   nnet_spec %>% 
   extract_parameter_set_dials() %>% 
   update(hidden_units = hidden_units(c(1, 27)))
# normalized workflow

Conclusions

Comparisons

Overall our model predicts Proviso township sale price better than the assessors model. This is likely because the assessors model is trained on the entirety of Cook County, while our model is trained exclusively on Proviso township. The assessors model appears to undervalue the properties in Proviso. It is also possible that the assessments are out of date due to the triennial cycle.

By class

oos_pred %>% 
  group_by(class) %>% 
  summarize(mailed_log_mean = mean(log(mailed_tot)),
            log_pred = mean(.pred),
            mean_log_sale = mean(log_sale_price, na.rm = T)) %>% 
  mutate(mailed_log_mean = round(mailed_log_mean, 2),
         log_pred = round(log_pred, 2),
         mean_log_sale = round(mean_log_sale, 2)) %>% 
  DT::datatable()

Density Plot

Our predictions are much more narrow than the actual sales. This is somewhat expected since the model tends to predict towards the average, however the implications of this is that lower value properties are over-assessed while higher value properties are under-assessed.

# pivot long to add source as color variable
pred_tb <-
  oos_pred %>% 
    group_by(pin) %>% 
    mutate(log_mailed = log(mailed_tot),
           log_mailed_adj = log_mailed + 2.5) %>% 
    select(c(log_mailed, .pred, log_sale_price, log_mailed_adj)) %>% 
    pivot_longer(cols = !pin,
                 names_to = 'source',
                 values_to = 'prediction')

pred_tb %>%
  filter(source != 'log_mailed_adj') %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_density(aes(prediction,
                   color = source))

pred_tb %>%
  filter(source != 'log_mailed') %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_density(aes(prediction,
                   color = source)) +
  xlim(10, NA)

Ultimately, I do not recommend that the assessor utilize my model. While it appears to perform well, it is likely an out of date assessment. Adjusting the log_mailed variable by adding 2.5, we see that the assessors adjusted assessments are much closer to the distribution of sale_price.
